                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d926">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/13367.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Special Agent <persName type="from">Canova</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Zacatecas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 2, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The convention of generals<note n="65" xml:id="d926fn65">See Mr. Belt’s telegram
                        of September 29, paragraph 3.</note> which met in Mexico City yesterday will
                    adjourn to hold an open caucus in Aguascalientes beginning on the 5th and
                    lasting until the 10th, when the convention will be called to order and will
                    terminate its work in Aguascalientes.</p>
                <p>A telegram received here today by Governor Acuña Navarro from General Lucio
                    Blanco, who signed as secretary of a committee of fifty-eight generals, gives
                    this information, and states that the First Chief has expressed his entire
                    conformity with this program and his willingness to abide by the decision of the
                    convention.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Canova</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
